<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[116, 72, 920, 121]]<|/det|>
A light spring \(AB\) has natural length \(a\) and modulus of elasticity \(5mg\). The end \(A\) of the spring is attached to a fixed point on a smooth horizontal surface. A particle \(P\) of mass \(m\) is attached to the end \(B\) of the spring. The spring and particle \(P\) are at rest on the surface.

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[116, 134, 920, 183]]<|/det|>
Another particle \(Q\) of mass \(km\) is moving with speed \(\sqrt{4ga}\) along the horizontal surface towards \(P\) in the direction \(BA\). The particles \(P\) and \(Q\) collide directly and coalesce. In the subsequent motion the greatest amount by which the spring is compressed is \(\frac{1}{5} a\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[116, 196, 272, 212]]<|/det|>
Find the value of \(k\).

One end of a light inextensible string of length \(a\) is attached to a fixed point \(O\). The other end of the string is attached to a particle \(P\) of mass \(m\). When the string makes an angle of \(60^{\circ}\) with the upward vertical, \(P\) becomes detached from the string. In its subsequent motion, \(P\) passes through the point \(A\) which is a distance \(a\) vertically above \(O\).
